  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real and deeply felt issue that affects many people, especially those from underrepresented groups. Growing up in Italy, I've seen how education systems can be biased, even when teachers try their best. My own experience as a barista and a mother has taught me that confidence comes from feeling supported, not just from knowing the subject. I've noticed that when someone is told they're not 'good at math,' it can make them doubt themselves, even if they've worked hard. This is especially true for girls and people from minority backgrounds who might already feel they don't belong in STEM fields. I think we absolutely should address stereotype threat because it's not just about numbers—it's about people. In my small town in Rome, I've seen how a single comment can make a child stop trying. To fix this, schools need to create safe spaces where everyone feels they belong, not just the 'typical' students. Teachers should be trained to recognize when a student is struggling with self-doubt and help them see their potential. It's not about changing the curriculum but about changing the way we talk about learning. I've also learned that being a good role model matters—showing kids that you're human and that it's okay to make mistakes can go a long way. In my own life, I've had to fight for the right to be seen as capable, and I hope others can do the same. We need to make sure that no one feels like they're 'not enough' in STEM because that's the most important thing—feeling like you belong.",
